commit_message:
Added check to prevent adding argument without help string

Added addition check in add_argument() to ensure it has help
message is always present per Amrith's suggestion in this review:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/261425/

Change-Id: Ic6486570d4beb138fdcd0c4e700ccc8d734d3e5e

commit_message:
Rename --profile to --os-profile

* The --profile global option is deprecated but will be supported
  through at least April 2017.
* Update man page

Closes-bug: #1571812
Change-Id: I2e623411a56096b4cc352f4eedbf770632ae2cc3

commit_message:
Clean up odl releases definition

Some snapshots are missing on
https://nexus.opendaylight.org/content/repositories/
This patch removes the missing ones and adjusts the default
odl release used.

Change-Id: I27d14d1c8c6c4197b20d3bdfe411c511f7e2b9e4
Closes-bug: 1571178

commit_message:
[cli-ref] Fix wrong delim splitting subcommands

- fixed issue where 'complete' generated wrong subcommands
  if they were hyphenated.
- fixed issue where 'hardcoded' subcommands (in clients.yaml)
  were ignored.
- added 'auth' to list of swift commands

commit_message:
[cli-ref] Added support for 'help' and 'version'

- added --version option.
- added support for printing help if no options given, or if
  'help' was used (i.e. 'openstack-auto-commands help')

openstack-manuals was also added to .gitignore so that
running the 'doc-tools-update-cli-reference' script will
not affect the os_doc_tools repo if the tool is run
within the repo.

Change-Id: I4c5ac6e7f207cd953040ce7b40cf1a5f13acf709

commit_message:
[cli-ref] Add support for multiple clients

- added ability to supply multiple clients at a time.
- added flag to continue processing clients even if an error
  occurs.
- fixed issue where an empty file was created if the client
  wasn't found.
- fixed issue where specifying --all-api and --all-manage would
  result in only --all-api being generated.

Change-Id: I8586279d884e1223ee7eb8ab12f50aa5ddc82561

commit_message:
Restart rather than reload in run_in_apache()

The service_reload('apache2') is not sufficient when upgrading
the charm from a scenario that did not run keystone as WSGI to
one that does. Apache is stopped and reload does not start it.
service_restart('apache2') fixes this.

Change-Id: Id999b162c780f9939884d3e21a20b337e595b58b
Closes-Bug: #1570579

commit_message:
Port more common unit tests to Python 3

* fakes/swift.py: replace httplib import with six.moves.http_client
* replace sorted(dict.iterkeys()) with sorted(dict)
* test_stream_codecs: use byte strings
* test_stream_codecs: add test on non-ASCII byte string
* Replace types.StringTypes with (bytes, six.text_type)
* tox.ini: add test_notification, test_remote and test_stream_codecs
  to Python 3

Partially implements: blueprint trove-python3
Change-Id: I9498ff6a8f0a7bae2e9292eb74fc9c44a400754a

With the advent of plugins and their settings files it has become
possible to disable_service in local.conf only to have the service
re-enabled in a plugin settings file. This happens because of
processing order.

To get around this the disable_service function now aggregates
requests into a DISABLED_SERVICES variable which is then processed
by perform_disable_service just after the "source" phase of
stacking. This allows local.conf to win the race which is likely to
more accurately reflect people's expectations.

Change-Id: I0f9403f44ed2fe693a46cd02486bd94043ce6b1a
Closes-Bug: #1504304
'}, {'created': '2015-10-09 16:37:23.000000000', 'message': 'Perform additional disable_service checks

With the advent of plugins and their settings files it has become
possible to disable_service in local.conf only to have the service
re-enabled in a plugin settings file. This happens because of
processing order.

To get around this the disable_service function now aggregates
service names into a DISABLED_SERVICES variable which is then checked
during enable_service. If something tries to enable something that

Then after all configuration has been sourced a final check is to
done by verify_disabled_services to confirm that something has not
manually adjusted ENABLED_SERVICES to overcome a previously called
disable_service. If something has, the stack dies with an error.

Closes-Bug: #1504304
'}]
commit_message:
Perform additional disable_service checks

With the advent of plugins and their settings files it has become
possible to disable_service in local.conf only to have the service
re-enabled in a plugin settings file. This happens because of
processing order.

To get around this the disable_service function now aggregates
service names into a DISABLED_SERVICES variable which is then checked
during enable_service. If something tries to enable something that
was previously disabled, a warning is produced in the log and the
service is not enabled.

Then after all configuration has been sourced a final check is to
done by verify_disabled_services to confirm that something has not
manually adjusted ENABLED_SERVICES to overcome a previously called
disable_service. If something has, the stack dies with an error.

Change-Id: I0f9403f44ed2fe693a46cd02486bd94043ce6b1a
Closes-Bug: #1504304

commit_message:
Fix openstack-base for centos-source

We had two issues here:

* mariadb-devel conflicts with Percona packages, so replace it with
  mysql-devel which pulls the right percona package.
* yum installed MySQL-python conflicts with pip installed one, only yum
  install MySQL-python for binary distro.

Change-Id: I61a638c977dd719c043d8fe0b0f935086b3d98ae
Closes-Bug: #1557890

commit_message:
Log the SHA of the Git ref for source builds

When using named refs in source builds, e.g. "reference = master", one
can't easily tell from the build output what SHA master actually pointed
to at that point and time. Update the debug output to include this.

Closes-Bug: #1566316

(cherry picked from commit cfd806aeff30818d2c1a909780f141ae0ac8dfef)

Conflicts:
	kolla/cmd/build.py

Change-Id: I7a88f31f8eaec96bf9ae9c66b4bae7315c6fc01e

commit_message:
Fix retrieving api_interface

In heterogeneous environment, api_interfaces are different each other.
So we should specify it from hostvars.

Backport: Liberty
Closes-Bug: #1530415
Change-Id: Id15d70bfb9ebb62a64a3847a6b77407efb171dbe
(cherry-picked from commit 903c7d4c3fc4283aa6ca7117e36ff90b92ae91a4)

commit_message:
Port test_template unit test to Python 3

* Fix test_template: replace server_id > 1 with len(server_id) > 1,
  server_id is a string. On Python 3, str cannot be compared to int,
  a TypeError is raised.
* Replace ConfigParser import with six.moves.configparser
* Replace basestring with six.string_types
* Replace dict.iteritems() with dict.items(). The iteritems() was
  removed in Python 3.
* Replace a/b with a//b to get integer on Python 3.
* tox.ini: add common/test_template.py to Python 3.4

Partially implements: blueprint trove-python3
Change-Id: Ibe2ccdcba7d55edcc014ea00c3b927d8201d6c1b

commit_message:
Vagrant: Allow running the "docker" command as the vagrant user

This adds the setting of DOCKER_HOST into the kuryr_rc file,
and moves the sourcing of said file into .bash_profile upon
user login. With this change, you can now login to the Vagrant
VM and run docker commands as the vagrant user.

Change-Id: If9b27b63b1dd017471714e18e70c2bf2138e65db
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

commit_message:
Fix ZUUL_REF on puppet-openstack-integration-checkout

Fix ZUUL_REF on puppet-openstack-integration-checkout JJB builder,
so we quote correctly, and avoid this error:

ZUUL_REF=${{ZUUL_REF:-None}}: bad substitution

Change-Id: I7424b20693856a978a406e0ac8554ca02ac871e7

commit_message:
add juju availability zone to ceph osd location when present

The approach here is to use the availability zone as an imaginary rack.
All hosts that are in the same AZ will be in the same imaginary rack.
From Ceph's perspective this doesn't matter as it's just a bucket after all.
This will give users the ability to further customize their ceph deployment.

Change-Id: Ie25ac1b001db558d6a40fe3eaca014e8f4174241

commit_message:
Fix keystone v2 support for multisite

Placement attr regions returned empty along with vim_project when
user provides keystone v2 in auth url

This fixes the vim-register for VIM with keystone v2 version

Closes-Bug: #1563661
Closes-Bug: #1563189
Change-Id: I439a21da6909ca6587dbb3d9de3dc478d02f7158

commit_message:
Allows DataSource's config field to have not dict type obj

CongressClient expects all datasource driver has dict object in
config field. It raises an error when a datasource doesn't have
any config.

This patch allows config fields to be None object.

Change-Id: I73354f1073f3f814854652eaeaa4b3bbe4bfcf7d

commit_message:
Fixed kwargs being defaulted to CONF values

The Trove code is full of numerous cases where kwargs are
defaulted to CONF values. This is an error-prone
way of setting up a default value, as python sets these one
time only. This fix accounts for that.

Change-Id: Icc0858ccb2d3e2584bf6f3d1542a7d631b251ac8
Closes-Bug: 1571076
(cherry picked from commit 64a869dbaf6ee583d667b4a6fd5fbbcd8902a646)

commit_message:
Move class properties to instances for dhcp/test_agent.py

Using class properties for tests always carries the risk of
conflicting use between test cases when tests are run in parallel.

Change-Id: I41034001a8674ad208c57f2f60266769390f924b
Related-Bug: #1569507

commit_message:
README.md: Cleanup documentation

Some things have changed since this was written, namely that kuryr itself
is started as part of devstack and the kuryr subnetpool is created. Also,
the instructions for using user_local.conf to add another Neutron plugin
need some updating.

Change-Id: I5f9a7ee1fff2607f5fbf2117e34ad4bc9b095b1f
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

One more issue:
Glanceclient does support keystone sessions as of liberty release (starting in 1.0.0), BUT global-requirements has python-glanceclient>=0.18.0, at which point keystone sessions was not supported.
So in practice it works, but technically it doesn't work for the lowest allowed version of python-glanceclient. What is the appropriate thing to do in this case?
Try to get global-requirements upped?

heatclient is fine with sessions supported as of the lowest allowed version python-heatclient>=0.3.0"}, {'account_id': 18591, 'date': '2016-04-15 18:35:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Just to clarify, sessions is officially supported by glanceclient as of liberty release. It's just that global requirements allows for older versions."}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2016-04-16 00:24:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Not quite sure about the Glance client version.  I know they always test according to the upper-constraints file.  Seems the right thing to do is change our requirements.txt file to glanceclient 1.0.0.  Maybe read through the release team's notes, and/or ask the release team on IRC.
https://github.com/openstack/releases/blob/master/README.rst"}, {'account_id': 18591, 'date': '2016-04-18 19:35:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Doug Hellmann suggested that we leave the requirements alone and just document that glance_driver requires glanceclient>=1.0.0. (Because upping our requirements would require upping the global-requirements which is generally avoided in stable branch.) Does that make sense?'}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2016-04-18 21:16:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Once we add that comment, this looks ready to go in."}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2016-04-18 21:17:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 18591, 'date': '2016-04-18 22:55:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-04-19 13:07:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

commit_message:
Use keystone sessions to authenticate

Tried out keystone session based authentication to solve our current
issue with token expiry. Just an alternate solution to

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/298960/1
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/298394/

Partial-Bug:#1563677
Partial-Bug:#1564115
Partial-Bug:#1563495
Closes-Bug:#1559362
Change-Id: I8a8a4fe5547b4aaa8a4735efd79857750e555578

commit_message:
Fix database poison warnings, part 3

The following warning appears in the unit test logs a number of times.
This patch fixes the warnings in ComputeAPIAPICellUnitTestCase.

    "UserWarning: This test uses methods that set internal oslo_db
state, but it does not claim to use the database. This will conflict
with the setup of tests that do use the database and cause failures
later."

Note that this warning is only emitted once per unit test worker, so new
offenders will show up in the logs each time you fix a test until they
are all gone.

Change-Id: Idcd733df2aafe809cb89f2a1db5df6ad227dd39c
Related-Bug: #1568414

commit_message:
Fix two issues that broke the gate

* Rename tenant to project in functional test In particular,
  rename "admin_tenant_name" to "admin_project_name" and
  rename "tenant_name" to "project_name". These configs have been
  renamed in tempest [1], so Magnum needs to adapt the change.
* Temporarily remove "subjectAltName" from CSR config, because
  it caused failure of certificate signing, possibly, due to a
  bug or imcompatible change in pyOpenSSL 16.0.0.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/301167/

Change-Id: I41438cbfaefd9d04d7e73a4f46f5ece1494b349c
Closes-Bug: #1568212
Closes-Bug: #1567691

[{'created': '2014-07-03 22:21:14.000000000', 'message': "Zero-copy object-server PUT requests with splice()

For non-chunked PUT requests, we can now use splice() to move the data
directly from the socket to disk without passing through user space.

Rather than write another nearly-identical splice loop with the fds
swapped and the threadpool moved, I introduce a pair of classes
SpliceFd and SplicePipe; they wrap up the fds and pipes involved in
splicing data. This lets us have just one class responsible for
calling splice() and handling timeouts, trampolines, and so on.

Handling PUT is a little more complicated than GET due to buffers in
libraries. In the process of reading the headers, the first part of
the request body (i.e. the object data) might get buffered. The object
server uses some low-level socket hackery to drain those buffers
without causing any more of the request body to get copied into user
space.

TODO: benchmark results go here (they'll be awesome!)

Change-Id: Ibf5ad68cdd4700df8b15d108e1bbf63c50c2478e

commit_message:
Zero-copy object-server PUT requests with splice()

For non-chunked PUT requests, we can now use splice() to move the data
directly from the socket to disk without passing through user space.

Rather than write another nearly-identical splice loop with the fds
swapped and the threadpool moved, I introduce a pair of classes
SpliceFd and SplicePipe; they wrap up the fds and pipes involved in
splicing data. This lets us have just one class responsible for
calling splice() and handling timeouts, trampolines, and so on.

Handling PUT is a little more complicated than GET due to buffers in
libraries. In the process of reading the headers, the first part of
the request body (i.e. the object data) might get buffered. The object
server uses some low-level socket hackery to drain those buffers
without causing any more of the request body to get copied into user
space.

TODO: benchmark results go here (they'll be awesome!)

Change-Id: Ibf5ad68cdd4700df8b15d108e1bbf63c50c2478e

This MariaDB setting uses the same timeout for SQL connections
as configured inside SQL Alchemy (pool_recycle) and prevent possibly

and respectively for Neutron
https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/stable/liberty/etc/neutron.conf#L761

commit_message:
Decrease MariaDB wait timeout

This MariaDB setting uses the same timeout for SQL connections
as configured inside SQL Alchemy (pool_recycle) and prevent possibly
SQL session build up due to a large default setting (8 Hours).

Nova and Neutron are using a idle_timeout of 3600 by default,
for example
https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/db/sqlalchemy/api.py#L101
and respectively for Neutron
https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/stable/liberty/etc/neutron.conf#L761

Change-Id: I273739c3c10616cac148aeb839154e0fb3359bca
Closes-Bug: #1571682
(cherry picked from commit a1636b3bb3c5c7588c8e92d4da45198929f7e833)

[{'created': '2016-04-18 08:56:08.000000000', 'message': 'Use "session_persistence" in data models for uniformity with API attribute

Currently API uses "session_persistence" attribute name for session
persistence while in data model the name is "sessionpersistence".
This naming difference makes things complicated and leads to errors
in case  wrong attribute name usage.

For example, if we try to create a pool with defined session persistence
from_dict method of the Pool data model tries to pop "session_persistence"
from a model_dict [1]. But in reality model_dict contains "sessionpersistence"
key due to the replacement that was done in from_sqlalchemy_model method [2]
according to the db model [3]. This will later lead to errors during
refreshing of a device when pool.sessionpersistence [4] returns a dict
instead of a SessionPersistence data model.

Kept sessionpersistence attribute in Pool data model for backwards
compatibility.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron-lbaas/blob/master/neutron_lbaas/services/loadbalancer/data_models.py#L350

commit_message:
Use "session_persistence" in data models for uniformity with API attribute

Currently API uses "session_persistence" attribute name for session
persistence while in data model the name is "sessionpersistence".
This naming difference makes things complicated and leads to errors
in case  wrong attribute name usage.

For example, if we try to create a pool with defined session persistence
from_dict method of the Pool data model tries to pop "session_persistence"
from a model_dict [1]. But in reality model_dict contains "sessionpersistence"
key due to the replacement that was done in from_sqlalchemy_model method [2]
according to the db model [3]. This will later lead to errors during
refreshing of a device when pool.sessionpersistence [4] returns a dict
instead of a SessionPersistence data model.

Kept sessionpersistence attribute in Pool data model for backwards
compatibility.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron-lbaas/blob/master/neutron_lbaas/services/loadbalancer/data_models.py#L350
[2] https://github.com/openstack/neutron-lbaas/blob/master/neutron_lbaas/services/loadbalancer/data_models.py#L67
[3] https://github.com/openstack/neutron-lbaas/blob/master/neutron_lbaas/db/loadbalancer/models.py#L148
[4] https://github.com/openstack/neutron-lbaas/blob/master/neutron_lbaas/services/loadbalancer/drivers/haproxy/jinja_cfg.py#L297

Conflicts:
	neutron_lbaas/drivers/octavia/driver.py
	neutron_lbaas/tests/unit/drivers/octavia/test_octavia_driver.py
	neutron_lbaas/tests/unit/services/loadbalancer/drivers/haproxy/sample_configs/sample_configs.py

Change-Id: Ib5efac45cf19acf0afe88a7ffa79514dd4129ed1
Closes-Bug: #1477348
(cherry picked from commit ae4687195c41929eb30dd462ad590f8d7e79e382)

commit_message:
newton: release python-novaclient 4.0

This is a major version release for some backward incompatible
changes.

Changes since 3.4.0:

f6efc86 Updated from global requirements
a602e59 Deprecate image list/show/delete/update CLIs/APIs
d133a66 Make functional tests work with v3 keystone
77f214b Updated from global requirements
a967e40 Fix typos in docstrings and comments
0634a38 Remove busted baremetal CLIs and API bindings
41fccc3 Updated from global requirements
e458fab Add default values for domain related options
a425702 Remove deprecated volume(snapshot) commands/bindings
b9807c0 Switch to 2.1 default api_version in v2.Client
7d8db71 [tests] initialize client objects inside setUp
51306fc Fix ServerGroup.NAME_ATTR
31c9e39 Using glance 'image-list'/'image-show' in boot help message

The upper-constraints bump is:

Ida4573431b4de24246e4f85e080c6e74ef1dfaf2

Change-Id: Idc23c88944db173edcfc697d054eaf0cf2cc73b6

[{'created': '2015-12-20 22:44:11.000000000', 'message': 'Gate: Fixed an empty service catalog error

After python-novaclient upgrade from 2.X to 3.X, the gate started
failing with the error below:

nova keypair-add --pub-key /home/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.pub default
ERROR (EmptyCatalog): The service catalog is empty.

This commit temporarily works around it by unseting OS_AUTH_TYPE
variable.

See: https://bugs.launchpad.net/python-keystoneclient/+bug/1519624

Change-Id: Ie194c5b4e3555572eba61767621e53b0b06b9ece
Closes-Bug: #1528059
'}]
commit_message:
Gate: Fixed an empty service catalog error

After python-novaclient upgrade from 2.X to 3.X, the gate started
failing with the error below:

nova keypair-add --pub-key /home/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.pub default
ERROR (EmptyCatalog): The service catalog is empty.

This commit temporarily works around it by unseting OS_AUTH_TYPE
variable.

See: https://bugs.launchpad.net/python-keystoneclient/+bug/1519624

Change-Id: Ie194c5b4e3555572eba61767621e53b0b06b9ece
Closes-Bug: #1528059

commit_message:
Add note on prerequisite of 'rpm' file extraction

As part of the manual cleaning step of firmware update the extraction
of firmware file with .rpm extension fails if commands `rpm2cpio` and
`cpio` are not present on the conductor. This doc note adds the
prerequisite information about `rpm2cpio` and `cpio` tools while using
a .rpm extn firmware file.

Partial-Bug: #1569900
Change-Id: I806980e62a9ad699b5a278a9dbc07682115d2a8f

LVM configuration is overwritten on nodes part of the hosts group.
This documentation explains that behaviour to a deployer, because
he may not think at first sight that its LVM configuration could
be overwritten in hosts others than the cinder ones.

Change-Id: I82769250f057bac28385cf63c8e1df7c7df511f5

(cherry picked from commit bb1db353230191f4ba2b5148846427ad6f715485)
'}]
commit_message:
Doc: Improved documentation about LVM overwrite behaviour

LVM configuration is overwritten on nodes part of the hosts group.
This documentation explains that behaviour to a deployer, because
he may not think at first sight that its LVM configuration could
be overwritten in hosts others than the cinder ones.

Change-Id: I82769250f057bac28385cf63c8e1df7c7df511f5
Closes-Bug: #1488532
(cherry picked from commit bb1db353230191f4ba2b5148846427ad6f715485)

commit_message:
add release:cycle-trailing tag

Add a new release model tag to describe projects that release slightly
out of phase with the rest of the release cycle, but that are part of
the release cycle. This should let us cover deliverables such as
packaging tools and deployment systems.

Change-Id: I783f6f6d55ab33386851910d09bf0e3f0efda404
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-04-14 09:35:13.000000000', 'message': 'Retire release:has-stable-branches tag

The release:has-stable-branch is useless and should be retired:

- The git repository is the true source of information whether
  a given repo has stable branches or not. The tag is therefore
  redundant, and often inaccurate (since it's not necessarily
  updated when a project creates stable branches).

- Having "stable" branches does not mean that the repository
  applies the common stable branch maintenance policy. This
  tag therefore does not convey any useful information for our
  downstream users. Whether a project follows stable policy or
  not is now described using the stable:follows-policy tag.

Change-Id: I7d7d24db0de4728977218f9b7fadc060f69c2e55
'}]
commit_message:
Retire release:has-stable-branches tag

The release:has-stable-branch is useless and should be retired:

- The git repository is the true source of information whether
  a given repo has stable branches or not. The tag is therefore
  redundant, and often inaccurate (since it's not necessarily
  updated when a project creates stable branches).

- Having "stable" branches does not mean that the repository
  applies the common stable branch maintenance policy. This
  tag therefore does not convey any useful information for our
  downstream users. Whether a project follows stable policy or
  not is now described using the stable:follows-policy tag.

Change-Id: I7d7d24db0de4728977218f9b7fadc060f69c2e55

commit_message:
Add UniqueConstraint for quota usages table

Currently, quota usages table doesn't contain any
UniqueConstraint. Under extreme circumstances such
as creating over 300 volumes for a new project
simultaneously, there are chances that multiple records
for same resource for same project can be created. Adding
UniqueConstraint can avoid this problem.

Change-Id: Iea6477034f20f04117c61cae37f3a0695fe68855
Closes-bug: #1484343

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-12 13:00:04.000000000', 'message': "Support volume backup of qcow2 format volume

Add support to qcow2 format disk for cinder-backup.
It will make drivers which use qcow2 as volume,
such as glusterfs etc,work together with cinder-backup,
and can also make nfs driver use qcow2 as volume be possible.

Changes:
* Add qemu-nbd support to cinder-backup. Qemu-nbd can mount qcow2
  volume as a raw device to the host.
* The backup_volume method in base class of remotefs driver
  will mount qcow2 volume as nbd device before call backup_service's
  backup method.

Change-Id: Ie00f07752a639228b355efa0d0d47526f177e0ce
Implements: blueprint support-volume-backup-for-qcow2

commit_message:
Support volume backup of qcow2 format volume

Add support to qcow2 format disk for cinder-backup.
It will make drivers which use qcow2 as volume format,
such as glusterfs etc,work together with cinder-backup,
and can also make nfs driver use qcow2 as volume be possible.

Changes:
* Add qemu-nbd support to cinder-backup. Qemu-nbd can mount qcow2
  volume as a raw device to the host.
* The backup_volume method in base class of remotefs driver
  will mount qcow2 volume as nbd device before call backup_service's
  backup method.

DocImpact
Change-Id: Ie00f07752a639228b355efa0d0d47526f177e0ce
Implements: blueprint support-volume-backup-for-qcow2

commit_message:
Fix retyping issue with multiple backends

Retyping a volume from one type to another was failing
if volume types are set to different backends.

This is because migrate_volume() was calling
objects.Volume.get_by_id with 'context' instead
of 'ctxt' causing get_by_id() to fail.

Note:

After making above correction I found that migrate
volume was getting stuck in 'deleting' state because
migrating_volume_completion() was passing
rpcapi.delete_volume() a 'sqlalchemy.models.Volume'
object instead of 'objects.volume.Volume' object
causing delete_volume to fail. So an extra get_by_id()
call was required to create a proper volume object for
passing to delete_volume.

Closes-Bug: #1530772

Change-Id: I25e42969d7a286a520ca14c391e5145f7a6912d8

commit_message:
Don't use default=None for config options

In the config module default=None is set as the default value,
so it isn't necessary to set it again when doing config options.

Change-Id: I887a5457aefc8e020a5e899c3414fd844998d210
Closes-Bug: #1323975

Cory, you are correct, but this design should never have been put in place and we have had multiple complaints, from operators, that this is not how it should be done.  Instead we should dynamically use the values from cinder.conf like is done for Nova.  

So, I think we should add a DocImpact and put a note about this in the README to make sure that people are aware of the change.  Otherwise, I think this is the right thing to do.'}, {'account_id': 7198, 'date': '2015-09-14 21:47:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Remove default quota data from DB

There is an issue where if cinder.conf has updated values for the
default quotas of volumes, gigabytes, or snapshots, those values do
not get updated. This is because in migration 21 sets the values for
these quotas in the DB, which overrides cinder.conf. This patch fixes
this issue by using the values from cinder.conf and not the values
from the DB.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I479958d1a8830097ee0b21e4f4c47a9abf3a07ec
Closes-Bug:1465393

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-12-09 12:44:54.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor Hitachi Block Storage Driver

Our drivers support FC and iSCSI protocols. Our drivers have two
interfaces, named HORCM and SNM2. In other words, four kinds of drivers
are performed on our code, HORCMFC, HORCMiSCSI, SNM2FC and SNM2iSCSI.

Because these drivers commonly use the our code, I found that it is
hard to maintain the present code. So I refactor our code drastically.

The new relationship of our code are following:
1. The most upper classes are HBSDFC and HBSDiSCSI. These classes
   inherit VolumeDriver class. These classes have HBSDCOMMON.
2. HBSDCOMMON class have common method with HORCM and SNM2.
3. HBSDHORCM and HBSDSNM2 classes inherit HBSDCOMMON.
   HBSDHORCM class have the characteristic methods for HORCM.
4. HBSDHORCMFC and HBSDHORCMiSCSI classes inherit HBSDHORCM.
5. HBSDSNM2FC and HBSDSNM2iSCSI classes inherit HBSDSNM2.
   These classes have characteristic methods respectively.

Change-Id: I5cab11a2b2d272503b8a57793dd86477e787eedb
Implements: blueprint refactoring-hbsd-driver

'}, {'created': '2016-01-14 05:36:20.000000000', 'message': "Refactor Hitachi Block Storage Driver

Our drivers have already supported FC and iSCSI protocols.
Our drivers have two storage interfaces, named HORCM and SNM2.
Our drivers have already supported three kinds of pattern on our code,
HORCMFC, SNM2FC and SNM2ISCSI.

This patch tries the following:
(1) refactor base libraries.
(2) refactor existing drivers based on libraries change.
(3) add a new pattern which is HORCM in iSCSI driver.(HORCMISCSI)

Because these drivers commonly use our code, I found that it is
hard to maintain the present code. So I refactor our code drastically.

And, Most code of this patch is (1) and (2),
item (3) can't be separated because they have dependencies.

The new relationship of our code are following:
1. The most upper classes are HBSDFC and HBSDISCSI. These classes
   inherit VolumeDriver class. These classes have HBSDCOMMON.
2. HBSDCOMMON class has common methods with HORCM and SNM2.
3. HBSDHORCM and HBSDSNM2 classes inherit HBSDCOMMON.
   HBSDHORCM class has the characteristic methods for HORCM interface.
   HBSDSNM2 class has the characteristic methods for SNM2 interface.
4. HBSDHORCMFC and HBSDHORCMISCSI classes inherit HBSDHORCM.
   HBSDHORCMFC class has the characteristic interfaces for HORCM and FC
   HBSDHORCMISCSI class has the characteristic interfaces for
   HORCM and ISCSI
5. HBSDSNM2FC and HBSDSNM2ISCSI classes inherit HBSDSNM2.
   These classes have characteristic interfaces respectively.

commit_message:
Refactor Hitachi Block Storage Driver

Our drivers have already supported FC and iSCSI protocols.
Our drivers have two storage interfaces, named HORCM and SNM2.
Our drivers have already supported three kinds of pattern on our code,
HORCMFC, SNM2FC and SNM2ISCSI.

This patch tries the following:
(1) refactor base libraries.
(2) refactor existing drivers based on libraries change.
(3) add a new pattern which is HORCM in iSCSI driver.(HORCMISCSI)

Because these drivers commonly use our code, I found that it is
hard to maintain the present code. So I refactor our code drastically.

And, Most code of this patch is (1) and (2),
item (3) can't be separated because they have dependencies.

The new relationship of our code are following:
1. The most upper classes are HBSDFC and HBSDISCSI. These classes
   inherit VolumeDriver class. These classes have HBSDCOMMON.
2. HBSDCOMMON class has common methods with HORCM and SNM2.
3. HBSDHORCM and HBSDSNM2 classes inherit HBSDCOMMON.
   HBSDHORCM class has the characteristic methods for HORCM interface.
   HBSDSNM2 class has the characteristic methods for SNM2 interface.
4. HBSDHORCMFC and HBSDHORCMISCSI classes inherit HBSDHORCM.
   HBSDHORCMFC class has the characteristic interfaces for HORCM and FC
   HBSDHORCMISCSI class has the characteristic interfaces for
   HORCM and ISCSI
5. HBSDSNM2FC and HBSDSNM2ISCSI classes inherit HBSDSNM2.
   These classes have characteristic interfaces respectively.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I5cab11a2b2d272503b8a57793dd86477e787eedb
Implements: blueprint refactoring-hbsd-driver

[{'account_id': 11215, 'date': '2016-02-08 22:11:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2016-02-08 22:16:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I'm not so sure that this is actually useful.  It is true that this fixes a a race between when this command started (or at line 295) and when this line runs.

But, I'm not convinced this matters for cinder-manage.  If someone runs cinder-manage, they're out of band of Cinder services anyway, and are already sitting in a giant race condition window just by virtue of using cinder-manage.

I think it would be more useful for this command to just do what it says it does rather than increasing the odds of it failing, when failing is not really helping anything."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-02-09 01:15:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
Removed potential races from volume update method

This patch changed volume update_host method to use compare-and-swap
update in order to remove potential races.

Specs: https://review.openstack.org/232599/

Change-Id: I02a5153746d374a7262f02794fa8f820687bdb39
Implements: blueprint cinder-volume-active-active-support

commit_message:
Fix usage of "cinder-volume" string

"cinder-volume" string was hardcoded in many places.
Fixed it by declaring a string constant and used that instead.

Change-Id: Ie7bbf6405ade698bc20c440f120875a26e45ed4e
Closes-Bug: #1548487

commit_message:
Pass volume size in GB to copy_volume function

We store volume size in GB so it's confusing to receive volume size
param in MB in volume_utils.copy_volume method's param. This patch
fixes it.

Co-Authored-By: Yuriy Nesenenko <ynesenenko@mirantis.com>
Closes-Bug: #1457238
Change-Id: I796d79a8a65df41f8f2b43345c04d2a87f8cf8a8

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

Simplified boolean variable check

Currently 'targets' variable is being checked
for empty list like 'if targets == []'.
The more standard approach is like 'if not targets'.

commit_message:
Nova and Brick remain their used iscsi sessions

Brick and nova are not synchronized with the same
connect_volume lock. This can cause nova or cinder
to logout of an iscsi portal when the other one is
attempting to use it. if nova and cinder are on the
same node.

This patch will just delete the device during
disconnect_volume, don't logout the session,
remain it for the next time.

Change-Id: Ia66de051d9dc6d1e81b2b91990245ab10a837086
Closes-Bug: #1429684

commit_message:
Added horizon documentation section for cinder

This introduces a new section in the cinder configuration doc where
deployers learn how to override the default horizon behavior with OSA.

Change-Id: I123e85a526e5e8d00cf937738148b260bd9353e0
Closes-Bug: #1518845
(cherry picked from commit 5fceb783bb2b179dbd2eaf95bd0f3d1d5d2d6bdc)

commit_message:
Don't use cached undercloud image for element repos either

These repos install packages on the undercloud, and if a package
install is mistakenly removed/broken it won't be caught if we use
the image that already has the packages installed.  This actually
happened in Ie204c5d0aa0f48d3d93d834b51a644d8562cd2fd which broke
all undercloud installs not using the cached image.

Change-Id: Ife3392f9c66616fb91c208fc75c38ee99246072b

commit_message:
Provide region when create environment

We can pass a region name when create environment by CLI.
But there is no ability to specify a region in dashboard.
This patch allows to associate an environment with
a region currently selected in horizon.

[{'created': '2015-12-22 19:35:24.000000000', 'message': "Fix scenario tests for octavia driver

ACTIVE while doing cleanups causing test failures.

default timeout is way too long.

commit_message:
Fix scenario tests for octavia driver

The current scenario tests were not waiting for the load balancer to become
ACTIVE while doing cleanups causing test failures.

Also, this increases a hardcoded timeout value of when a load balancer is
deemed to be stuck.  It was too short for the gate and the nested VMs issue of
boot taking 5-8 minutes.  I've increased it to 10 minutes.

A timeout was also needed when testing connectivity to a VIP because the
default timeout is way too long

Change-Id: I667af547296ac707a6176d5c400ce025366e65ba
(cherry picked from commit cb4af16b532e93c475be626692bc3c7d8741d072)

commit_message:
Replace File with Concat in dependencies

Up to 2.0.0 concat was done as a define which contains File. Starting
from 2.0.0 concat::fragment define was rewritten as provider. This patch
replaces dependencies to File from concat::fragment with Concat to
enable concat ~> 2.0.0

Change-Id: Ifccc1bf2260dbbceb75b6bbe1d6b5bbbbb657a12

commit_message:
Totally drop Qpid support

Qpid was removed in Mitaka from Oslo Messaging, so now we can
drop it in manifests.

Change-Id: I336c99b7709f061734ca09128a366361f13a934e

commit_message:
Totally drop Qpid support

Qpid was removed in Mitaka from Oslo Messaging, so now we can
drop it in manifests.

Change-Id: I2536cc611b29c1cb75b942cf8c103aafe8c1f49a

commit_message:
Add option to auto enable from VPNaaS in Horizon

This change simple provides an option to inspect the neutron_plugin_base
and enable vpnaas within horizon if the option is found.

Depends-On: I2343f91e5ae1664fc8ab9ba1fbc3196b4d92078c
Depends-On: Ie9f89f7d2a942df40841d72c82f3a34315c6bed9
Change-Id: Ie21eaf940f54a0c2175ab3232d84cd3ea7fd8128
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Support task concurrency

Without this changes Astute will ignore information about
task strategy and will run as many as possible tasks on suitable nodes.
The only limit which can be used in this case is node concurrency,
but it will decrise deployment performance

Also change log level for message about concurrency
from info to debug, because in mostly cases they are required
only for developers

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1571014

Change-Id: I4f27da4abdaf4939002b62d05a44e23d3f1a3d5e

commit_message:
Clear DVR MAC on last agent deletion from host

Once all agents are deleted from a host, the DVR MAC generated
for that host should be deleted as well to prevent a buildup of
pointless flows generated in the OVS agent for hosts that don't
exist.

Closes-Bug: #1568206
Change-Id: I51e736aa0431980a595ecf810f148ca62d990d20
(cherry picked from commit 92527c2de2afaf4862fddc101143e4d02858924d)

[{'created': '2016-04-14 06:28:33.000000000', 'message': "Add ALLOCATING state to routers

This patch adds a new ALLOCATING status to routers
to indicate that the routers are still being built on the
Neutron server. Any routers in this state are excluded in
router retrievals by the L3 agent since they are not yet
ready to be wired up.

This is necessary when a router is made up of several
distinct Neutron resources that cannot all be put
into a single transaction. This patch applies this new
state to HA routers while their internal HA ports and
networks are being created/deleted so the L3 HA agent
will never retrieve a partially formed HA router. It's
important to note that the ALLOCATING status carries over
until after the scheduling is done, which ensures that
routers that weren't fully scheduled will not be sent to
the agents.

An HA router is placed in this state only when it is being
created or converted to/from the HA state since this is
disruptive to the dataplane.

This patch also reverts the changes introduced in
Iadb5a69d4cbc2515fb112867c525676cadea002b since they will
be handled by the ALLOCATING logic instead.

Co-Authored-By: Ann Kamyshnikova <akamyshnikova@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: John Schwarz <jschwarz@redhat.com>

APIImpact
Closes-Bug: #1550886
Related-bug: #1499647
Change-Id: I22ff5a5a74527366da8f82982232d4e70e455570
(cherry picked from commit 9c3c19f07ce52e139d431aec54341c38a183f0b7)
"}]
commit_message:
Add ALLOCATING state to routers

This patch adds a new ALLOCATING status to routers
to indicate that the routers are still being built on the
Neutron server. Any routers in this state are excluded in
router retrievals by the L3 agent since they are not yet
ready to be wired up.

This is necessary when a router is made up of several
distinct Neutron resources that cannot all be put
into a single transaction. This patch applies this new
state to HA routers while their internal HA ports and
networks are being created/deleted so the L3 HA agent
will never retrieve a partially formed HA router. It's
important to note that the ALLOCATING status carries over
until after the scheduling is done, which ensures that
routers that weren't fully scheduled will not be sent to
the agents.

An HA router is placed in this state only when it is being
created or converted to/from the HA state since this is
disruptive to the dataplane.

This patch also reverts the changes introduced in
Iadb5a69d4cbc2515fb112867c525676cadea002b since they will
be handled by the ALLOCATING logic instead.

Co-Authored-By: Ann Kamyshnikova <akamyshnikova@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: John Schwarz <jschwarz@redhat.com>

APIImpact
Closes-Bug: #1550886
Related-bug: #1499647
Change-Id: I22ff5a5a74527366da8f82982232d4e70e455570
(cherry picked from commit 9c3c19f07ce52e139d431aec54341c38a183f0b7)

commit_message:
Fixing assignment-from-no-return issue.

While expecting a value on a function call, It is a good practic to
have a return statement instead of pass.

This change moves all of the configuration options previously defined
in "nova/paths" to the new centralized "nova/conf" directory.

move one additional directory upwards with "../../" to preserve the
correct default value.

commit_message:
Config options: centralize base path configuration

This change moves all of the configuration options previously defined
in "nova/paths" to the new centralized "nova/conf" directory.
A subsequent patch will then improve the help texts.

As the helper functions to create specific directories are only used
for the default values of other config options, they got moved too.

The default value of the config option "pybasedir" gets determined by
the directory which contains it. The old directory was "nova/" and
new directory is "nova/conf/". That made it necessary to move one
additional directory upwards with "../../" to preserve the correct
default value.

bp centralize-config-options-newton

Change-Id: I65fc8d83da660e131e89ce5849e7535e969adcb2

commit_message:
ODL: Add precommit to create/update_bgpvpn

Adds following checks to ODL driver:
1. create_bgpvpn: Only type l3 is allowed
2. create_net_assoc: Allow network to be associated with only one bgpvpn
3. create_router_assoc: Allow only one router to be associated with a
bgpvpn

Change-Id: I03859bb457a7eed469d003e13ae855e9ba6b11c6
Closes-bug: 1560842

commit_message:
ADDRESS_SCOPE_MARK_IDS should not be global for L3 agent

Otherwise agent becomes unable to handle more than 1024 routers
(including deleted routers) and starts failing.

It should be enough to distinguish address scopes inside router namespace,
so this patch moves ADDRESS_SCOPE_MARK_IDS set to the RouterInfo class.

Closes-Bug: #1566291
Change-Id: I1e43bb3e68db4db93cc1dfc1383af0311bfb0f2d
(cherry picked from commit 1cb43734808eded87210d2957d56b70c514d55c3)

commit_message:
Fix doc build if git is absent

When building packages if git is absent, then we should not set
html_last_updated_fmt. It can still be set via the -D switch
when building with sphinx-build.

Change-Id: Ib289335198b0fe0a00922cbfe5c7fd7ff438ffcf
Closes-Bug: #1552251

[{'created': '2016-04-09 18:24:36.000000000', 'message': "Check if a exception has a code on it before read the code

In 'nova.volume.cinder.API.initialize_connection' method, all exceptions
threw by 'terminate_connection' will be caught and logged. When log the
exceptions, the code try to record the 'code' attribute of the exception
since the code is expecting a CinderClientException or NovaException[1].
But if the some else exception(like TypeError) which doesn't have a code
on it was threw up, we will got a AttributeError.

This commit add logic to check if the exception has a code on it before
try to read it.

[1]https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/13.0.0.0rc3/nova/volume/cinder.py#L437

Change-Id: I42fd2f2b77c41a60dfaf0cc882a344596d50daf5
Closes-Bug: #1564551
(cherry picked from commit 2135a3f55ff2222ec9c0fe7064aa339a430af4ee)
"}]
commit_message:
Check if a exception has a code on it before read the code

In 'nova.volume.cinder.API.initialize_connection' method, all exceptions
threw by 'terminate_connection' will be caught and logged. When log the
exceptions, the code try to record the 'code' attribute of the exception
since the code is expecting a CinderClientException or NovaException[1].
But if the some else exception(like TypeError) which doesn't have a code
on it was threw up, we will got a AttributeError.

This commit add logic to check if the exception has a code on it before
try to read it.

[1]https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/13.0.0.0rc3/nova/volume/cinder.py#L437

Change-Id: I42fd2f2b77c41a60dfaf0cc882a344596d50daf5
Closes-Bug: #1564551
(cherry picked from commit 2135a3f55ff2222ec9c0fe7064aa339a430af4ee)

commit_message:
Revert split into 2 shell scripts

Previously, it was attempted to split deb-openstack-pkg-tools.yaml into
2 shell scripts instead of one, to attempt to work around the sbuild
relogin problem. This didn't work, and since, a workaround was found.

Therefore, this patch cleans-up the mess from previous attemp, and
remerges into a single shell script.

Change-Id: Ibfd2dd812d78e2af6afd4a6739a8915214b8fa32

I've got some changes queued up for another revision based on inline discussion, but I'm not going to rev this just yet.  There's a few areas still under discussion that it would be nice to decide on:

1) Should the subport attribute be immutable?  Should you be able to boot a Nova VM with a subport and have Neutron automatically adapt the port to no longer be a subport?  I don't feel too strongly either way, yet.

2) Do we need to create a port with an attribute saying it's capable of being a parent port?  From an API perspective, it seems awkward and ideally shouldn't be required.  There's some suspicion that implementing this for the existing OVS support may require it.  I don't think it's strictly required, but it could be required to avoid making this too invasive to how the ovs agent works today.  Some further discussion about how this might work with ml2+ovs could help inform this decision.  I'm going to look a bit closer to make a more informed opinion.

3) Armando has some general concerns that I need to better understand and work through.  We'll be in the same place at a conference on Monday so I hope to get a chance to chat and work through this some more.  I will report back to here, of course."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-11-15 21:15:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

This revision contains the following changes:

1) Re-add the is_parent attribute, because it seems beneficial overall.  It does allow Neutron to reject a request sooner if child ports are not supported by the backend.  It also seems that it could help support this feature in the existing OVS agent.

2) Rename encap_type ane encap_id to segmentation_type and segmentation_id, to better match fields that cover a similar thing for provider networks.

3) Update what happens if Nova (or whatever) were to try to update binding:host_id of a child port (honor the request instead of making it fail).

4) Note that multiple levels of nesting is allowed per the API, but may be limited by the Neutron backend.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-20 20:23:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

Thinking about this, I think I can see the thing that's confusing here (from a logical model perspective).

Trunk ports are ports - fine, we're stripping off some of their traffic before it makes it onto their parent network, but they are definitely ports.

Subports really aren't ports.  They're actually something *plugged into* a port.  You couldn't attach a VM to a subport - the model doesn't work - and I think that's because they're effectively already in use.  Is that a concept we can work with or should I just shut up?  (Gratifying as it would be to have the perfect logical model, I think working and useful is more important; if this is an extension, it can be superseded by a new and different extension if we really did need a change.)"}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-12-08 22:35:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Sub-ports aren't ports if you think of ports as the VIFs. However, if you think of the port as the thing that contains the IP allocation, security group filtering policies, dhcp reservations, etc, then a sub-port makes sense as a Neutron port.

All of the normal port attributes apply to a sub-port, the only difference is that the binding process involves sending tagged traffic out a VIF shared with another port."}, {'account_id': 6558, 'date': '2015-12-09 06:20:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(1 comment)

I think we should also discuss about the port binding with this proposed change - i.e. how are we thinking of making that work in this model.'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-12-09 06:28:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

For the ref implementation, port binding would be relatively straightforward. When the subport is updated to be part of a trunk, the binding details would indicate that the port is encapped with segmentation details on another port. Then the mechanism driver would determine if it can tag to the parent port and mark the port as bound if it can. Then the agent will wire up the tags and mark the port as ACTIVE when it's done. 

So the same async workflow the OVS mechanism and agent use now."}, {'account_id': 11604, 'date': '2015-12-10 08:52:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

@Kevin Benton,Russell Bryant

just reading over your irc logs i noticed one thing that concerned me regarding the ovs agent implementation. its not needed for the spec but just taught i would point it out.

when ye were discussing moveing port between bridges using an atomic del-port -- add-port command i dont think that will work with vhost-user in client mode. 

ovs/dpdk currently only supports client mode. in client mode ovs creates the unix socket used for configuration management and qemu polls for it and connect when it appears.
the socket is created as part of the add-port and is deleted in the del-port.(it can also be created non atomically by seting the interface type to dpdkvhostuser on an existing port) 

if you move the port using a del/add-port combination as an atomic action, assuming ovs deletes the unix socket and qemu has already connected to it, then qemu will use the old file descriptors and ovs will use the new ones for the recreated socket.

if ovs does not recreate the socket when its an atomic "move" then it should work ok. similarly if this is done before qemu has conneted to the socket then it should also be fine. this is not an issue when using a tap device as the add/del-port commands do not manage the lifetime of the tap device.

dpdk 2.3ish will hopefully add support for server mode vhost-user where the unix socket is create by qemu instead of ovs. in that event moving a vhost-user port should work the same way as standard tap devices.'}, {'account_id': 20007, 'date': '2016-01-05 14:38:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

[{'created': '2015-11-10 19:16:18.000000000', 'message': "Proposed changes to vlan-aware-vms.

This patch includes some proposed changers to the vlan-aware-vms spec.
I'd like to propose that we revisit the idea of using only the existing
Neutron port resource instead of creating a new trunk-port resource.

I have attempted to capture it in updates to the spec itself.  In short
though, it seems to me that using the existing port resource is
sufficient.  I believe it will result in a simpler implementation (though
that will have to be proven with code).  Finally, it doesn't require any
changes to projects that interface with Neutron and handle VIF port
binding (like Nova, but also Kuryr or anything similar).

Change-Id: I8563e54cc984b60f2be2eb7cc2e3c6fc60e6de20
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Proposed changes to vlan-aware-vms

This patch is a new version of the vlan-aware-vms spec, re-introducing
a new trunk resource, but in a way that does not affect nova.

Co-Authored-By: Bence Romsics <bence.romsics@ericsson.com>
Change-Id: I8563e54cc984b60f2be2eb7cc2e3c6fc60e6de20

commit_message:
Allow chainloading of Inspector ramdisk over UEFI

To send the Inspector ramdisk over HTTP rather than TFTP, we must first
send an iPXE boot image that knows how to speak HTTP, and then instruct
it to "chainload" the inspector ramdisk. Previously, we could only do
this if the machine being introspected had BIOS firmware. However, most
modern servers now use UEFI firmware, which requires a different iPXE
boot image (as described at http://ipxe.org/howto/chainloading).

We must specify the initrd in the iPXE `kernel` line to avoid the
problem described at http://forum.ipxe.org/showthread.php?tid=7589.

Change-Id: I9cb102178bee8039a8cfc157154ecbd315aba871

Install UEFI version of iPXE ROM in /tftpboot

This allows Ironic Inspector to introspect machines which have UEFI
firmware.

Change-Id: I293444bc8b0ed577451e17fcaedfae9ce1946b1d

commit_message: Unify value of "xsd:boolean" in Dataprocessing API This patch makes values of "xsd:boolean" in Dataprocessing API v1.1 to be uniform. Currently, the values of "xsd:boolean" is some times presented by True or true. As my knowledge, the value should be true. Reference link: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1308491/xsdboolean-element-typed -accept-true-but-not-true-how-can-i-make-it-accept Change-Id: Ic17ef63affb4c6d6072b501c394bf2b2c1196afb Partial-Bug: #1562766

commit_message:
Glance:"Create image" Response parameters table contains redundant value.

This patch removes "location" in Response parameters table and keeps
"locations" in sample response of Create image api.

Change-Id: Ia89d2ffa4fe41dc3c66c25ec6c6d180e0a484ce7
Closes-Bug: #1538905

commit_message:
Adding three parameters: access, os-deny_access and access_list.

This patch added added three parameters: access, os-deny_access
and access_list into "Grant access", "Revoke access" and
"List access rules", sequently.

Closes-Bug: #1567242

commit_message:
Adding "volume_type" parameter into Volume types

This patch added "volume_type" parameter into "Create volume type",
"Update volume type" and Update extra specs for a volume type.
This parameter is missed.

commit_message: Rewrite parameter in Identity API ext v3 OS-TRUST This patch edits role paramter in Identity API ext v3 OS-TRUST: http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-identity-v3-ext.html#identity_v3_OS-TRUST-ext + roles: should be defined as: A list of role objects. Includes id, name, and links for any roles. Roles define which actions users can perform. The patch also decribe the role object with more details. Change-Id: Iba3937e70f79de49a9f5561a884b5db9993fb56f Closes-Bug: #1564781

'}]
commit_message:
Revert "Add BaseEnumField valid_values introspection"

This patch broke object hasher values for objects using Enum.

Among other things, it broke neutron job running against oslo master:

http://logs.openstack.org/periodic/periodic-neutron-py27-with-oslo-master/4d64e7c/testr_results.html.gz

This reverts commit 0c7ec37d3aa5941b1d8d8bf4bfe78b6ff90d9211.

Change-Id: I993e7dab772f395aca6c9149adf509a7e86e8e47

commit_message:
libvirt: fix missing python-libvirt issue

When python-libvirt is missing we must not use libvirt module exception
and just reraise error as-is.

Change-Id: If000dafdf9b7b08e108f6f91ae6ec967923eeb1d
Closes-bug: #1572016

commit_message:
Add options to auto enable VPNaaS

This change makes it possible for the neutron role to enable VPNaaS using
the reference OpenSwan driver by simply setting the `vpnaas` option within
the **neutron_plugin_base** list. This capability has been within the role
for some time however never specifically configured.

The change will bind the vpnaas agent to any location that is within the
neutron_l3_agent group. The agnet brings with it a new ini file and a new
entry point for config_template overrides. The vpnaas packages will be
installed when the agent is enabled within the target location of the
running agent services.

Change-Id: Ie9f89f7d2a942df40841d72c82f3a34315c6bed9
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit 94994ef2e782ec7ae112241a6c2d76673d51f490)

commit_message:
Fixing D204, D205, D208, and D211 pep8

Curently tox ignores D204, D205, D208, and D211.
D204: 1 blank required after class docstring.
D205: Blank line required between one-line summary and description.
D208: Docstring is over-indented.
D211: No blank lines allowed before class docstring.
This patch removes tox ignores and fix docstrings.

Change-Id: I691f728e7b12ad4fcd542a116fd3d491e83393a4

commit_message:
Implement higher job timeout for Ansible role jobs

Some of the OpenStack-Ansible (OSA) roles construct enough of
an OpenStack environment and execute enough functional testing
for the job to easily reach the 30 min default time limit.

This patch implements a higher limit to cater for these jobs
to ensure that OSA can properly execute functional testing in
the roles without having to compromise o quality to accommodate
a short job timeout.

Change-Id: I780b735de54c23cfea14ddafa8ad39aff16e92eb

commit_message:
Enable non-voting keystone tempest plugin tests

Turn on the keystone tempest plugin tests. From now on, tests that are
only related to the keystone API, will be placed there.

To run only keystone tempest plugin tests, we use::

    $ tox -e all-plugin -- keystone

 * non-voting so we can see that it works
 * master-only
 * run only against keystone

Change-Id: I070e1f40ecaa5d23a68c4ac23b542631ea3e2309
Partially-Implements: bp keystone-tempest-plugin-tests

commit_message:
Rewrite the polling logic for SSH

This patch is rewriting code responsible for polling the data in the SSH
module. Prior to this patch the logic had different code paths depending
on the host operational system used and the polling was causing paramiko
to hang in some cases (see bug linked in this commit message). The logic
is now simpler and OS agnostic.

Closes-bug: #1571492
Change-Id: Ibfb201c94229a9c7297a5018c86bbacba8225eba

commit_message:
Add .yaml extension to package installs

Change Ie204c5d0aa0f48d3d93d834b51a644d8562cd2fd added
package-installs to openvswitch and ironic-conductor elements.
The package-installs file has to have a .yaml or .json extension,
otherwise they will not be used.

Change-Id: Ie76ab99d49ec5aee2a94743ac05a0eee53150d97

commit_message:
Grub stage1 shall be installed on all of disks

Otherwise, under some conditions, first disk (hd0 or sda) could be
filtered out, thus making a node totally unbootable due to missing
bootloader code.

This is a backport from master.
Original-Id: Ib28a821f17816e318db87df2bb9830bf3a157286
Closes-Bug: #1567930

Change-Id: Idd5b2353e77981f7323c1c7afaaf3f897af78e79

commit_message:
Add a function to decide if using cache is appropriate

As we we make more use of the cache the logic to decide
if we can use the cache will be better placed in a single
function where is can be easier understood.

Change-Id: Ic1149a61c46f6d1d4bb9649da4710543962cd285

commit_message:
Removing tox ignore D400.

Currently tox ignores D400 (D400: First line should end with a period).
This change removes D400 ignore.
All pep8 violatios are fixed.

Change-Id: I9190a15a36c90d3c60a9c520cb53d5f182b0c4e9

[{'created': '2016-03-08 11:57:37.000000000', 'message': 'Add specification for Watcher Scoring Module

This specification defines a Scoring Module which attempts to
standarize interactions between Watcher Decision Engine and
scoring engines, which can be implemented using external machine
learning tools or frameworks.

Change-Id: I3325f80924b70376def77e692296079dd45cc495
Implements: blueprint scoring-module
'}, {'created': '2016-03-08 13:51:19.000000000', 'message': 'Add specification for Watcher Scoring Module

learning tools or frameworks.

commit_message:
Add specification for Watcher Scoring Module

This specification defines a Scoring Module which attempts to
standarize interactions between Watcher Decision Engine and
scoring engines, which can be implemented using external machine
learning tools or frameworks.

Change-Id: I3325f80924b70376def77e692296079dd45cc495
Implements: blueprint scoring-module

Commit hash looks right to me. Good to get another (final?) release of Liberty out to include these changes.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-04-15 16:18:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

- gate-releases-tox-validate http://logs.openstack.org/25/306525/1/check/gate-releases-tox-validate/643e482/ : SUCCESS in 4m 08s

- gate-releases-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/25/306525/1/check/gate-releases-pep8/c9a3956/ : SUCCESS in 2m 46s
- gate-releases-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/25/306525/1/check/gate-releases-docs/4554251//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 7m 37s'}, {'account_id': 12898, 'date': '2016-04-18 06:44:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(3 comments)

I'm not sure if this is enough to -1 a liberty release for cinder but:

 ce2715d Dont query image metadata for empty volume list

https://review.openstack.org/#/q/I51733e1e3c526f4ca46e2826c242924407fabbe4,n,z

Is in master and liberty but *not* on mitaka.  We either need to land it on mitaka or revert on liberty."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2016-04-18 12:21:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2016-04-18 15:15:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Tony: Thanks, this has now been merged into Mitaka.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2016-04-18 18:19:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

We don't normally want stable releases to add new dependencies. Is that new pytz dependency OK with the stable team?"}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2016-04-18 18:24:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Note that the pytz dependency wasn't added via stable/liberty backports -- it was a requirement in liberty 7.0.0 that wasn't documented."}, {'account_id': 12898, 'date': '2016-04-19 02:13:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

> We don't normally want stable releases to add new dependencies. Is
 > that new pytz dependency OK with the stable team?

Hi Doug,

IMO it's okay.  It is a bit grey but the use of  pytz has been there in all liberty releases (see: http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/cinder/tree/cinder/image/cache.py?h=7.0.0#n15 )

It's just that Babel was pulling in pytz (See: http://logs.openstack.org/22/278422/1/check/gate-cinder-python27/1443f6d/tox/py27-1.log.txt.gz )

So I agree that technically we're adding a requirement to cinder in reality we're just making an existing requirement explicit.  Any operator running 7.X should *already* have pytz installed.

This may have a small impact on downstream packagers but as it's already packaged and installed via the transitive deps it should cause too much pain."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2016-04-19 15:35:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Add Agent DevStack Backend

* Add a new backend for DevStack allowing the Agent
  backend to be configured.
* Change the agent to choose a sane port by default, it's extremely
  unlikely anyone is exposing the agent on port 53 intentionally.
* The agent itself is not yet configured, this will come later as it
  involves refactoring most of the BIND non-agent backend into a lib.
* Fail when the user asks for the agent backend, without also enabling
  the agent service.

Change-Id: Iedde58f4f5a2ea89cb9da78aaec1853208af8fc9

commit_message:
Remove baremetal client code in favor of upstream client

This removes the initialization of the ironicclient from within
tripleoclient and instead uses the plugin packaged in ironicclient
itself.

Change-Id: Ic55d16ee65cc7ec1524e074ba83f6ae36739c7e4
Depends-On: I91ea4f4a63b0e7a8ea004c47422d19ca0f288dcd

fix samples references for 2 files

This fixes the samples references for ``servers-actions.inc`` and
``servers-multiple-create.inc`` and drops the warnings count to 195.

commit_message:
Adds base in-tree functional testing of the dhcp agent (OVS)

Adds some utility methods and a couple of base test cases that
can be added to. These first tests exercise the ovs driver (dnsmasq)
and so the code is organised accordingly - OVS specific test cases
are defined in a DHCPAgentOVSTestFramework

Partial-Bug: #1469065
Co-Authored-By: Cedric Brandily <zzelle@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Sergey Belous <sbelous@mirantis.com>

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/contrib/functional-testing.filters

Change-Id: Ic9d5a2f2b8014e4d81f5e5f6fa58b119a86de075
(cherry picked from commit 31bdb9bffd9d9d979f53f954d165526438cf0c57)

commit_message:
Update servers.inc to be as accurate as api-site

This updates servers.inc which had a rough path during conversion. The
GET servers/details was lost entirely.

It updates a number of parameters to distinguish ones that are only in
the queries, as well as fixes references to short names that collided.

It updates the UPDATE call to only specify request parameters which
you can actually update.

It introduces the notation object.field for parameters that are
embedded in other objects. This is a new concept, but one way we can
clear up that the uuid in the parameter list is really networks.uuid.

It also deletes the old hand rolled servers.rst, which drops the
warnings count by nearly 100.

Part of bp:api-ref-in-rst

Change-Id: Ie7693a5888efa913118244a0837e6c0177965d48

commit_message:
Add purge_config option for the cinder config

Adding a purge_config option for the cinder config resource. Adding
this option for ease of management and readability. If users wish they
can use this to ensure that only the options they are setting make it
into the configs.

Change-Id: Ia8fda598e4f26a2a9673995a9f47299386daec30

commit_message:
Fix longtime tests

The core problem is in usage `while True:` to wait element,
but implicit_wait delegates its to browser already.
Just we need to catch StaleElement exception, reload
chain of element parents and then to execute command again.

Change-Id: I9c94b8adb04489c9675644d1501919af35e5bf99
Closes-Bug: #1570803

commit_message:
Vitrage - Zuul/Jenkins fix

layout.yaml - Removed Python3 jobs temporarily until
     we set our local tox to run py34 instead of py3.
vitrage.yaml - Fixed hook function to use source

URGENT - Thanks :)

Change-Id: I58994cf77608df5310d6a2b45de195dcc718cfe2

commit_message:
Use Chrome for JS unit tests

PhantomJS has setup issues and is slowing down the gate with false
failures. We should change to Chrome until Phantom is more
reliable, at which point this patch can be reverted.

Change-Id: I4bf1c1e8e26ac708bd35145aff98562f30b3a050
Closes-Bug: 1568325

commit_message:
Rebase on new pypowervm retry default

Recent pypowervm change 76b1cc23dd2d0625e0e9a6d97e6ea460bc8e50e8 changed
the default number of retries from three to six.  Rebase a unit test
accordingly:  an old networking-powervm needs to work whether it is
running against a new or an old pypowervm.

Change-Id: I6417aef92adc560fa7cbd37aad21f2a7e665b264

commit_message:
Smooth out glance api servers getter

* get glance api servers list from one entry point for http(s)
* set the following descending priority for getter:
  - hiera glance_api_servers raw list
  - get_ssl_property() return
  - hiera glance_endpoint ip address
  - $management_vip

Change-Id: I80c45d1c6cdabfd8aa239ae61d8c4add5e9e8cbe
Closes-Bug: #1568088
Closes-bug: #1569443

commit_message:
Add /v3 endpoint support for cinderclient

Add support for Cinder API /v3 endpoint.
A couple of unit tests for /v3 endpoint were added to v3/test_shell.py
to ensure that the v3 shell works, and to also test that modules work
with:
from cinderclient.v2.availability_zones import *
syntax.

Change-Id: I6ae0ada221bebb4ab1850d9c99b10fcbb585201f
Implements: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/python-cinderclient/+spec/add-v3-endpoint-support

commit_message:
Sort versions by semver

The ordering in the output file is currently string-ordering, which
puts 1.10.0 before 1.2.0.  Use semver ordering to get this in the
right order.

Change-Id: I27291789193b9ff872a56cbefcb8271c8a765127

[{'created': '2016-03-22 21:30:08.000000000', 'message': 'Compute test "wait_for_resource_deletion" fails

Test fails when tempest_roles=admin in tempest.conf
but passes when tempest_roles=member.  This is
because the admin role will return a value whether
the image is active or deleted which sends the test
in an endless loop until it fails do to time out.
Change addresses bug by checking status of returned message.

Change-Id: I4e6937c992398cfc7db5391cfabb101aaefdb7e6
Closes-Bug: #1557088
'}, {'created': '2016-03-22 21:44:26.000000000', 'message': 'Compute test "test_create_delete_image" fails

Test fails when tempest_roles=admin in tempest.conf
but passes when tempest_roles=member.  This is
because when checking for delete the admin role will
return a value whether the image is active or deleted
which sends the test in an endless loop until it fails do to time out.
Change addresses bug by checking status of returned message.

Change-Id: I4e6937c992398cfc7db5391cfabb101aaefdb7e6
Closes-Bug: #1557088

commit_message:
"is_resource_deleted" fails to verify delete

Is resource deleted in images_client.py isn't adequate
for admin role because when checking for deleted images
the admin role returns a value whether the image is active or deleted.
This causes an endless loop if a call is waiting on a response of true.

Change-Id: I4e6937c992398cfc7db5391cfabb101aaefdb7e6
Closes-Bug: #1557088
Closes-Bug: #1564661
Closes-Bug: #1564614

to switch the URL scheme to https://

'cinderclient_ext' to get more shorter module names.

commit_message:
Restart services when trigger from principle

Check to see if a restart trigger has been sent by the principle,
if it has then right the trigger uuid in to the neutron.conf to
trigger a service restart

Change-Id: I19649cb73dad94f4fe24412c0b8c37a28f30047d
Partial-Bug: 1571634

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-04-19 02:16:04.000000000', 'message': '[install] do not install/start/enable nova-cert service

According to http://docs.openstack.org/developer/nova/man/nova-cert.html:

---snip---
nova-cert is a server daemon that serves the Nova Cert service for X509
certificates. Used to generate certificates for euca-bundle-image. Only
needed for EC2 API.
---snap---

Because we do not install the EC2 API we do not need the nova-cert
service.

Change-Id: I0c27c89fb6f6b982ce227273e040216828b40135
'}, {'created': '2016-04-19 03:35:48.000000000', 'message': '[install] do not install/start/enable nova-cert service

commit_message:
[install] do not install/start/enable nova-cert service

According to http://docs.openstack.org/developer/nova/man/nova-cert.html:

---snip---
nova-cert is a server daemon that serves the Nova Cert service for X509
certificates. Used to generate certificates for euca-bundle-image. Only
needed for EC2 API.
---snap---

Because we do not install the EC2 API we do not need the nova-cert
service.

Change-Id: I0c27c89fb6f6b982ce227273e040216828b40135

Validate attributes restrictions

Since Nailgun contains attributes restriction
mechanism it's possible to verify attributes
restrictions. This commit applies restrictions
checks into validation for both node attributes
and cluster attributes.

Closes-Bug: #1567394

commit_message:
Add 'binary' and 'disable-reason' into os-service

there are references in os-service.inc to binary and disable-reason
but the definitions are missing in parameters.yaml

definitions are here:
https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/api/openstack/compute/schemas/services.py

Part of bp:api-ref-in-rst

commit_message:
use path as resource id when missing RESELLER prefix

we don't have an id if RESELLER prefix is not in path. this causes
an id to be autogenerated making each request a completely different
resource id.

this patch changes it so we just default to path as our id if one
cannot be computed.

Change-Id: I5775406a84b5f2ad0f95f366b7deca210d2f8e87
Closes-Bug: #1566940

This extra step is not necessary and only a waste of time.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2016-04-18 20:20:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I agree. Frankly, the Ubuntu packages should not assume use of SQLite. commit_message:
Put correct release version into metadata.yaml for plugin_reboot

As we are using FPB from master branch we can not rely on
generated metadata.yaml file because it can contains wrong release.
Allow FuelPluginBuilder to modify metadata.yaml by data received from
nailgun

Change-Id: Ic020df8b7e677830f5a71be18b6a241417946b08
Closes-bug:1569327

commit_message:
Switch main bootstrap source repository to online one

In case of deploying Fuel Master node on a pre-provisioned
server, we should use online repositories instead of local
ones, to build the Ubuntu bootstrap.

Change-Id: If4a5d8d715740289e85f8004a5655b35c25c9c6b
Closes-Bug: #1570747

subject: add configuration files required for kilo based deployments
messages:
[{'account_id': 9592, 'date': '2016-04-19 03:09:49.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-04-19 03:10:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/47/307547/1/check/noop/fc6da0a/ : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 12715, 'date': '2016-04-19 12:32:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

There are a couple things I don't like about this.

1. The other config files are topology based. These configs mix a lower footprint topology with some workarounds for kilo, without describing which is which.

2. Where are there kilo TripleO packages? There is no stable/kilo branch to build them from.

The first one is a bit cosmetic, and I could get over it. We need to figure out a better scheme for configuration files anyways, and this could easily be cleaned up when that is better defined.

The second is a blocker though. Without stable/kilo branches, there are no kilo packages in RDO, and without kilo packages, there is no kilo undercloud image and no reason to have kilo configs in an upstream TripleO repo."}, {'account_id': 9592, 'date': '2016-04-19 13:35:15.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

going to move this configuration to another tool.'}]

commit_message:
pin google-api-client to 0.9.4

google-api-client requires Ruby version ~> 2.0, so we need to pin to
0.9.4.

See https://github.com/google/google-api-ruby-client/issues/397

Change-Id: I8a6e5e56c1e6d36e66febd878507f8eef5c5a738
Closes-Bug: #1570627
(cherry picked from commit a301dd0439459457278041716e6ff700dd8d83b0)

to the client code to be able to reprocess stored
introspection data

commit_message:
Translations: Refactor

Merge extract_messages and extract_messages_log into one function
extract_messages_python since these are always used together.

Merge propose_python and propose_django in one function propose,
call the extract_messages_* function outside of it.

Refactor python and django handling in a single function that can
be invoked twice instead of duplicating lines.

Change-Id: Ib92df685f9268e2429a119f619c1ab7e9ff1b82a

commit_message:
Move OpenStack-Ansible CentOS7 jobs to experimental queue

As the work to implement CentOS7 support in OpenStack-Ansible is
low priority work which is being done over several cycles, the
jobs to implement this are being moved to the experimental queue.

This will reduce the OpenStack-Infra resources wasted and only
implement the jobs on-demand.

Change-Id: I52e044a6d47691cca52e6c76f6b6268c01003434

commit_message:
Move tempest-cli-improvements to implemented

This commit moves tempest-cli-improvements to implemented and also
removes "tempest run" things from the spec. Because refactoring existing
commands is different from making a new command. We should split the
thing. And adding tempest-run command bp is already proposed[1].

[1] I588c4a9b940937f9ad4f85138da58e551d10c2eb

Change-Id: I2c316bddcfdf6b15eed2823eb7ca177e9b97141c

commit_message:
Add group_vars for swift_remote_all hosts

When expanding hostvars for a different host, ansible will attempt to
expand the vars that are passed through a filter (netloc or netorigin
for example). This causes the ansible_remote_all hosts to fail out
during the SSH key sync phase.

In order to get this to work successfully we need to define the vars
that are being expanded (even though they aren't technically required by
the remote_hosts or swift plays) so that the remote hosts can access the
local hosts' hostvars.

Change-Id: I7f74a8404a8c805cdaf78596b1b32e7de95238c0

[{'created': '2016-03-04 11:52:33.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] Allow 'openstack baremetal configure boot' to guess the root device

This change simplifies using Ironic root device hints for people who only need
to change the default strategy of selecting the default device.
E.g. we have a use case for selecting the first device instead of the smallest,
so that the root device does not change after upgrade Kilo -> Liberty.

This change introduces 2 new arguments to the command:
--detect-root-device is a new strategy to use
  If this argument is provided, the client will try to detect the root device
  based on the stored introspection data. Possible strategies:
  * smallest (the same thing as IPA does by default)
  * largest (the opposite thing - pick the largest device)
  * first (first device alphabetically, roughly matches Kilo ramdisk)
--root-device-minimum-size minimum size of the considered devices
  The default value of 4 GiB matches what IPA does.

Note that for these arguments to work, this command should be run after
introspection. A separate documentation change will be posted for that.

Change-Id: I9f19554c5e7f34c8f63c1603c32b4d470fb12592
